article.headline: Charles Smith lights up Kings with career-high 32

images.name: Smith, Charles 020221 inline
images.caption: In scoring a career-high 32 points, Charles Smith had good reason to be happy.

article.linkText: Spurs hit first 11 3-point tries to outgun Kings
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- It only seemed as though every shot the San Antonio Spurs took landed at the bottom of the net. The Spurs connected on their first 11 3-point attempts and Charles Smith scored a career-high 32 points in a 115-92 win Thursday night over Sacramento in the final regular-season matchup between the teams. The Kings won the first three. Reserve Malik Rose added 23 points and Tony Parker had 15 for San Antonio. Tim Duncan had 13 rebounds but scored only nine points, the first time he didn't have at least 10 this season. David Robinson had his fourth double-double in the past six games with 10 points and 11 boards. "The guys played great tonight," said Duncan, who is averaging 25 points a game. "I think I held us back in the first. I sat down and we really started rolling." The Spurs didn't miss a 3-pointer until Steve Smith was short in the waning seconds of the third period. San Antonio ended the night with 12 3-pointers on 16 tries, with Charles Smith making four and Parker three. "It was ridiculous," said Sacramento center Vlade Divac, who finished with seven points and nine rebounds. "But that wasn't the reason (we lost). The reason was that we didn't play defense." San Antonio was shooting better than 60 percent for most of the night, but fell back to 52 percent after reserves played most of the fourth quarter. Bobby Jackson paced the Kings with 18 points off the bench. Chris Webber was held to 13 points, 12 below his average, while Peja Stojakovic, averaging 22 points, had only 11. Four other Kings finished in double figures. Webber said the Kings were happy to see the ball out of Duncan's hands, and he credited the rest of the Spurs for stepping up. "You have to give the win to the whole cast because the whole cast played well," he said. "It wasn't surprising -- it was disheartening." The Spurs were up by as much 40 in the third quarter before coach Gregg Popovich started emptying his bench. Jackson scored 10 of his points in the fourth quarter when the Kings were able to chip away at the lead and make the final score look a little less lopsided. San Antonio built a double-digit lead in the game's first four minutes behind the deadeye shooting of Parker and Smith. The pair connected on nine of their 11 shots in the period, including all five 3-pointers. On defense the Spurs smothered the Kings, who managed to hit only eight of their 22 shots, and dominated the boards. A 3-pointer by Rose as time ran out in the quarter gave the Spurs a 40-25 lead. Robinson went to the bench with his third foul midway through the second, but Sacramento kept its offensive game on the perimeter and kept missing. A tip-in by Rose put San Antonio up by 20 at 56-36 late in the half. The Kings shot 40 percent from the floor on the night, including only 3-of-16 outside the arc.

Game notes
The Spurs' 98 points after three quarters set a new season high for the team, while the 40 points in the first quarter and 68 at the half matched season marks. ... San Antonio is 32-4 when leading at the half, but 3-14 when trailing at the break. ... Steve Smith made one 3-pointer and now has 998 in his career. ... Sacramento rookie forward Gerald Wallace missed the game with chicken pox, and Spurs guard Stephen Jackson left the Alamodome before the game complaining of nausea. ... The Kings, with the league's best record of 40-14, are now 12-12 on road. They have the league's best home record -- 28-2.
